The auction includes 80 billion CFA Francs ($132 million) in seven-year bond at a 5.8% rate and a 30 billion CFA Franc ($49.5 million) 10-year bond at 5.9%, said the lead managers from NSIA bank and SOGEBOURSE, the investment banking arm of bank SocGen. The bonds, which will be sold in units of 10 000 CFA Francs ($16.21), are being marketed to investors across West Africa’s CFA currency zone from February 12-25. Ivory Coast, Francophone West Africa’s largest economy and the world’s biggest cocoa producer, has tapped international bond markets several times in the past few years. ($1 = 595.10 CFA Francs) --Reuters--